00:30:32,600 --> 00:30:33,700
but hey,
don't forget to buckle up.

558
00:30:33,900 --> 00:30:36,900
Remember safety.
A good driver is a safe driver.

559
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:39,700
A safe driver is what?
Yes.

560
00:30:40,400 --> 00:30:42,900
[Turns radio off]

561
00:30:56,100 --> 00:30:58,500
Morning, ma'am.

562
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:19,100
[Electrical buzzing]

563
00:32:36,500 --> 00:32:37,100
I love that idea.

564
00:32:37,300 --> 00:32:38,300
It's pretty cool,
isn't it?

565
00:32:38,500 --> 00:32:41,000
Yeah, I love it.

566
00:32:42,900 --> 00:32:45,400
[Speaking spanish]

567
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:43,700
[Ding]

568
00:33:43,900 --> 00:33:44,500
Can I help?

569
00:33:44,700 --> 00:33:45,900
Yeah. I have
an appointment

570
00:33:46,100 --> 00:33:47,100
at gable
enterprises.

571
00:33:47,400 --> 00:33:49,800
That's impossible.

572
00:33:54,100 --> 00:33:54,900
What's happening?

573
00:33:55,100 --> 00:33:56,000
Guard: Nothing.

574
00:33:56,200 --> 00:33:57,500
Just tell me
what's happening.

575
00:33:57,700 --> 00:33:59,400
Got to go, sir.
We're remodeling.

576
00:33:59,600 --> 00:34:00,000
No, you're not.

577
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:01,700
What are those people
doing back there?

578
00:34:01,900 --> 00:34:02,500
It's none of
your business.

579
00:34:02,700 --> 00:34:05,400
If you don't tell me what's
happening, I'll report you!

580
00:34:05,600 --> 00:34:08,000
You're trespassing.

581
00:34:08,700 --> 00:34:11,000
Right.

582
00:34:39,100 --> 00:34:40,700
Marlon!

583
00:34:40,900 --> 00:34:41,500
Truman.

584
00:34:41,700 --> 00:34:42,400
What are you
doing here?

585
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:43,500
[Whispering]
I gotta talk to you.

586
00:34:43,700 --> 00:34:45,000
It's a bad time, ok?
I'm way behind.

587
00:34:45,200 --> 00:34:48,100
I'm onto something, marlon.
Something big.

588
00:34:48,500 --> 00:34:49,300
You ok?
You look like shit.

589
00:34:49,500 --> 00:34:51,500
I think I'm mixed up
in something.

590
00:34:51,700 --> 00:34:52,000
Mixed up in what?

591
00:34:52,200 --> 00:34:53,200
There's no point
trying to explain it,

592
00:34:53,400 --> 00:34:56,400
but a lot of strange things
have been happening.

593
00:34:56,400 --> 00:34:58,700
[Stammering]

594
00:35:00,600 --> 00:35:02,600
The people on the elevator.

595
00:35:02,800 --> 00:35:04,200
There was
no backing on it.

596
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:06,200
I looked out.
There was people there.

597
00:35:06,400 --> 00:35:08,700
And on the radio
on the way to work,

598
00:35:08,900 --> 00:35:10,100
it starts
following me along,

599
00:35:10,300 --> 00:35:12,100
talking about everything
that I'm doing.

600
00:35:12,300 --> 00:35:12,800
You know what I mean?

601
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:15,100
Truman, look, this is
one of your fantasies.

602
00:35:15,300 --> 00:35:16,700
I think
this is about my dad.

603
00:35:16,900 --> 00:35:17,900
Your dad?

604
00:35:18,100 --> 00:35:18,900
I think he's alive.

605
00:35:19,100 --> 00:35:21,500
Yeah. I'll tell you
about it later.

606
00:35:21,700 --> 00:35:23,400
I'm definitely
being followed.

607
00:35:23,700 --> 00:35:25,900
Who?

608
00:35:26,500 --> 00:35:27,700
It's hard to tell.

609
00:35:27,900 --> 00:35:30,800
They look just like
regular people.

610
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:34,800
How about those two?

611
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:36,500
Truman: I don't know.

612
00:35:36,800 --> 00:35:37,000
Could be.

613
00:35:37,300 --> 00:35:40,300
It's when I'm unpredictable,
that's--they can't...

614
00:35:43,500 --> 00:35:44,800
Did anything happen?

615
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:45,200
No.

616
00:35:45,400 --> 00:35:47,500
Mm-hmm. We gotta
get out of here.

617
00:35:47,700 --> 00:35:48,200
You ready to go?

618
00:35:48,400 --> 00:35:49,700
No. I just
came here. Come on.

619
00:35:49,900 --> 00:35:50,900
I told you I can't.

620
00:35:51,100 --> 00:35:53,400
[Growls]

621
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:58,100
You're gonna get both our asses
fired. You know that.

622
00:35:58,300 --> 00:35:59,900
Ok, man,
let's do it.

623
00:36:00,100 --> 00:36:01,600
What?
Whatever you say.

624
00:36:01,800 --> 00:36:02,600
I'm game.

625
00:36:02,800 --> 00:36:03,600
Marlon: What are you
talking about?

626
00:36:03,800 --> 00:36:06,800
Yes, siree. Your birthday
comes but once a year.

627
00:36:09,800 --> 00:36:12,500
Truman: Maybe I'm being
set up for something.

628
00:36:12,700 --> 00:36:15,500
You ever think
about that, marlon?

629
00:36:15,600 --> 00:36:16,500
Like your whole life

630
00:36:16,700 --> 00:36:19,100
has been building
towards something?

631
00:36:19,300 --> 00:36:20,600
Mmm, no.

632
00:36:20,800 --> 00:36:22,400
When you were
hauling chickens

633
00:36:22,600 --> 00:36:24,400
in the summer
for kaiser,

634
00:36:24,600 --> 00:36:25,800
what was
the furthest

635
00:36:26,100 --> 00:36:28,100
you ever got
off the island?

636
00:36:28,300 --> 00:36:29,500
Went all over.

637
00:36:29,700 --> 00:36:32,600
Never found a place
like this, though.

638
00:36:32,900 --> 00:36:34,500
Look at that sunset,
Truman.

639
00:36:34,700 --> 00:36:36,500
It's perfect.

640
00:36:36,700 --> 00:36:38,600
Yeah.

641
00:36:38,800 --> 00:36:40,900
That's the big guy.

642
00:36:41,200 --> 00:36:43,400
Quite a paintbrush
he's got.

643
00:36:43,700 --> 00:36:45,900
Yup.

644
00:36:47,900 --> 00:36:50,700
Just between you
and me, marlon...

645
00:36:52,100 --> 00:36:54,700
I'm going away
for a while.

646
00:36:55,300 --> 00:36:57,200
Really?

647
00:36:57,500 --> 00:36:58,400
Yeah.

648
00:36:58,600 --> 00:37:01,300
Mother: Oh, little angel.

649
00:37:01,800 --> 00:37:04,200
[Women laugh]

650
00:37:06,900 --> 00:37:09,300
Oh, my little clown.

651
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:13,300
Old carrot top.

652
00:37:13,500 --> 00:37:15,900
The best photos.

653
00:37:17,400 --> 00:37:18,100
Ohh.
Ohh.

654
00:37:18,300 --> 00:37:19,900
We should be getting you
home, mother.

655
00:37:20,100 --> 00:37:23,000
Hold on a minute.
Here's us at mount rushmore.

656
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:25,700
Do you remember, Truman,
when dad was still with us?

657
00:37:25,900 --> 00:37:27,300
That was quite a drive.

658
00:37:27,500 --> 00:37:30,300
You slept
the whole way there.

659
00:37:30,300 --> 00:37:31,300
Truman:
It looks so small.

660
00:37:31,500 --> 00:37:34,100
Things always do
when you look back, darling.

661
00:37:34,300 --> 00:37:34,900
Oh, look, Truman.

662
00:37:35,100 --> 00:37:37,800
The happiest day
of our lives.

663
00:37:39,900 --> 00:37:41,000
Oh, look.

664
00:37:41,200 --> 00:37:43,100
Jean, Jodie, joanne.

665
00:37:43,300 --> 00:37:44,900
Doesn't she look
beautiful, Truman?

666
00:37:45,100 --> 00:37:46,800
Well, she still does.

667
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:50,100
And there's lots of pages
left over for baby photos.

668
00:37:51,300 --> 00:37:54,300
I would like to hold
a grandchild in my arms

669
00:37:54,600 --> 00:37:54,900
before I go.

670
00:37:55,100 --> 00:37:57,400
Angela, we really should
be getting you home.

671
00:37:57,600 --> 00:37:58,100
I'll take her.

672
00:37:58,400 --> 00:38:00,400
No, no, no.
You stay, relax.

673
00:38:00,600 --> 00:38:01,000
Enjoy yourself.

674
00:38:01,200 --> 00:38:03,200
Your favorite show
will be coming on.

675
00:38:03,400 --> 00:38:06,000
Besides, we have
something to discuss.

676
00:38:06,200 --> 00:38:08,900
A certain person's
birthday.

677
00:38:08,900 --> 00:38:10,500
Oh, I see.

678
00:38:10,700 --> 00:38:12,000
TV announcer: And there'll be
another episode

679
00:38:12,200 --> 00:38:14,000
of I love Lucy
same time tomorrow.

680
00:38:14,200 --> 00:38:17,400
But right now it's time
for golden oldies.

681
00:38:17,700 --> 00:38:20,400
Tonight, we present
the enduring, much-loved classic

682
00:38:20,600 --> 00:38:22,500
show me the way to go home.

683
00:38:22,700 --> 00:38:24,500
A hymn of praise
to small-town life,

684
00:38:24,800 --> 00:38:26,800
where we learn that you don't
have to leave home

685
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:28,500
to discover
what the world's all about,

686
00:38:28,700 --> 00:38:31,600
and that no one is poor
who has friends.

687
00:38:31,800 --> 00:38:34,700
Full of laughter and love,
pain and sadness,

688
00:38:35,400 --> 00:38:36,800
but ultimately redemption,

689
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:38,800
we share the trials
and tribulations

690
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:39,600
of the abbott family.

691
00:38:39,800 --> 00:38:42,800
Note the touching performance of
Ronald brierly as Uncle buddy.

692
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:44,800
And that scene with the bowl
of cherries is gonna have you

693
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:47,600
splitting your sides
with laughter all over again.

694
00:38:47,800 --> 00:38:48,900
And there'll be tears, too,

695
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:52,000
when David and Jennifer
are reunited.

696
00:38:52,500 --> 00:38:55,100
But enough from me.
Let's join the Abbotts

697
00:38:55,300 --> 00:38:57,700
in Camden village.

698
00:39:15,600 --> 00:39:18,000
[Birds chirping]

699
00:39:19,400 --> 00:39:21,800
[Radio static]

700
00:39:22,200 --> 00:39:23,400
Oh.

701
00:39:23,600 --> 00:39:26,100
Thank you, sweetie.

702
00:39:29,800 --> 00:39:31,400
I need to talk to you,

703
00:39:31,600 --> 00:39:33,100
but let's go outside.

704
00:39:33,300 --> 00:39:36,300
Oh, sweetie, I'd love to,
but I'm really late.

705
00:39:36,500 --> 00:39:39,000
What's your rush?

706
00:39:39,500 --> 00:39:40,300
Surgery.

707
00:39:40,500 --> 00:39:42,200
There was that elevator
disaster downtown.

708
00:39:42,400 --> 00:39:43,700
It was on the news
last night.

709
00:39:43,900 --> 00:39:45,900
This cable just snapped.
This elevator,

710
00:39:46,100 --> 00:39:48,300
it just plummeted down
10 flights.

711
00:39:48,500 --> 00:39:49,400
The non-union workers.

712
00:39:49,600 --> 00:39:51,600
Just monsters.
You know, that building,

713
00:39:51,800 --> 00:39:53,100
it's right next door
to where you work.

714
00:39:53,300 --> 00:39:55,200
Can you imagine if you
had been in there?

715
00:39:55,400 --> 00:39:57,100
It's not even worth
thinking about.

716
00:39:57,300 --> 00:39:58,100
Anyway,
I have an amputation

717
00:39:58,300 --> 00:40:01,300
on one of the young
women in that elevator.

718
00:40:01,300 --> 00:40:02,400
She's very young.

719
00:40:02,600 --> 00:40:03,300
It's very sad.

720
00:40:03,500 --> 00:40:05,400
Anyway, wish me luck.

721
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:08,300
I'll cross my fingers
for you.

722
00:40:46,400 --> 00:40:48,600
[Brakes squeal]

723
00:40:48,800 --> 00:40:51,200
Uh, excuse me.
Hi. Excuse me.

724
00:40:51,400 --> 00:40:53,100
May I help you?

725
00:40:53,300 --> 00:40:53,600
Oh, uh...

726
00:40:53,800 --> 00:40:56,800
Yes. I'm looking for my wife,
nurse Burbank.

727
00:40:58,100 --> 00:40:58,600
It's very important.

728
00:40:58,800 --> 00:41:01,200
I'm afraid that
that's not possible.

729
00:41:01,500 --> 00:41:02,500
She's in pre-op.

730
00:41:02,700 --> 00:41:04,100
Sure.

731
00:41:04,300 --> 00:41:06,000
Ok, fine.

732
00:41:06,200 --> 00:41:07,600
Can you pass along a message?

733
00:41:07,800 --> 00:41:08,400
I'll try.

734
00:41:08,600 --> 00:41:10,300
Can you tell her
I had to go to Fiji

735
00:41:10,500 --> 00:41:12,100
and that I'll call her
when I get there?

736
00:41:12,300 --> 00:41:15,000
When you--
when you get to Fiji?

737
00:41:15,300 --> 00:41:15,900
You got it.

738
00:41:16,100 --> 00:41:18,600
Fine. I'll tell her.

739
00:41:18,600 --> 00:41:21,100
Thank you so much.

740
00:41:46,600 --> 00:41:47,700
Sorry.

741
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:50,300
It's ok.

742
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:58,300
He's here.

743
00:41:58,800 --> 00:42:01,700
Meryl: I know, I know.
Shh, shh, shh.

744
00:42:02,100 --> 00:42:04,300
Scalpel.

745
00:42:06,100 --> 00:42:08,400
Ahem.

746
00:42:09,200 --> 00:42:12,000
I'm now making
my primary incision

747
00:42:13,300 --> 00:42:15,900
just above the right knee.

748
00:42:17,600 --> 00:42:19,900
[Loud clang]

749
00:42:22,100 --> 00:42:23,000
Nicely done.

750
00:42:23,200 --> 00:42:26,000
This isn't
going to be pretty.

751
00:42:26,100 --> 00:42:28,700
It's just
beautiful.

752
00:42:28,700 --> 00:42:30,100
Beautiful job.

753
00:42:30,300 --> 00:42:33,300
I'll just let someone else
tidy up here.

754
00:42:57,700 --> 00:43:00,300
I'm sorry to keep you.

755
00:43:00,400 --> 00:43:02,700
Oh, that's ok.

756
00:43:03,700 --> 00:43:04,200
How can I help?

757
00:43:04,400 --> 00:43:06,500
I would like to book
a flight to Fiji.

758
00:43:06,700 --> 00:43:09,500
When would you like
to leave?

759
00:43:12,200 --> 00:43:14,500
Today.

760
00:43:24,800 --> 00:43:26,800
[Beep]

761
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:27,800
[Beep]

762
00:43:28,100 --> 00:43:30,400
[Beep]

763
00:43:30,400 --> 00:43:31,100
I'm sorry.

764
00:43:31,300 --> 00:43:34,300
I don't have anything
for at least a month.

765
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:35,800
A month?

766
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:38,500
It's the busy season.

767
00:43:39,900 --> 00:43:41,300
You want to book the flight?

768
00:43:41,500 --> 00:43:43,500
It doesn't matter.

769
00:43:43,700 --> 00:43:46,500
I'll make other
arrangements, ok?

770
00:43:49,700 --> 00:43:52,300
Man:
Last call for Chicago!

771
00:43:53,500 --> 00:43:55,900
All aboard!

772
00:43:59,100 --> 00:44:00,900
[Whistles]

773
00:44:01,100 --> 00:44:03,400
Thank you.

774
00:44:05,300 --> 00:44:07,900
Windy city, here we come.

775
00:44:09,100 --> 00:44:11,400
Hi.
Hi.

776
00:44:13,200 --> 00:44:14,800
Hello.

777
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:17,200
Hi.

778
00:44:17,400 --> 00:44:18,400
Truman: Sisters.

779
00:44:18,600 --> 00:44:21,100
Hey, mom, isn't that--

780
00:44:21,600 --> 00:44:24,200
mom: Shh.
Face the front.

781
00:44:32,500 --> 00:44:34,900
[Gears grind]

782
00:44:38,200 --> 00:44:40,600
[Gears grind]

783
00:44:44,200 --> 00:44:46,100
[Gears grind]

784
00:44:46,300 --> 00:44:47,900
[Engine stalls]

785
00:44:48,100 --> 00:44:49,400
[Radiator hissing]

786
00:44:49,600 --> 00:44:52,400
Everybody off.
We've got a problem.

787
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,500
I'm sorry, son.

788
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:29,100
His father was from
Chicago, wasn't he?

789
00:45:29,300 --> 00:45:31,700
No. His dentist
was from pensacola.

790
00:45:31,900 --> 00:45:33,200
His father
was from des moines.

791
00:45:33,400 --> 00:45:35,300
But how come he wants
to go to Chicago?

792
00:45:35,500 --> 00:45:38,600
He's not going to Chicago.
He's not going anywhere.

793
00:45:38,800 --> 00:45:41,400
He has to have it out
with Meryl.

794
00:45:41,600 --> 00:45:44,000
[Pluto barks]

795
00:45:57,000 --> 00:45:59,200
Truman?

796
00:46:03,100 --> 00:46:05,600
Honey, are you ok?

797
00:46:05,800 --> 00:46:08,100
Get in.

798
00:46:10,300 --> 00:46:12,600
Truman.

799
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:15,200
Look.

800
00:46:17,900 --> 00:46:20,100
What?
Shh.

801
00:46:20,300 --> 00:46:20,900
I predict

802
00:46:21,100 --> 00:46:22,700
that in just a moment

803
00:46:22,900 --> 00:46:25,700
we will see a lady
on a red bike,

804
00:46:26,500 --> 00:46:28,100
followed by a man
with flowers

805
00:46:28,300 --> 00:46:30,900
and a volkswagen beetle

806
00:46:31,200 --> 00:46:32,400
with a dented Fender.

807
00:46:32,600 --> 00:46:34,100
Truman, please.

808
00:46:34,300 --> 00:46:36,700
Truman: Look.

809
00:46:40,200 --> 00:46:42,600
Lady...

810
00:46:43,500 --> 00:46:45,800
Flowers...

811
00:46:45,900 --> 00:46:48,300
Both: And...

812
00:46:49,800 --> 00:46:51,500
Truman, this is silly.

813
00:46:51,700 --> 00:46:53,000
There it is!
There it is!

814
00:46:53,200 --> 00:46:56,100
There's that dented
beetle! Yes!

815
00:46:56,400 --> 00:46:58,700
Aaaaaah!

816
00:46:58,700 --> 00:47:01,100
Ha ha ha!

817
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:04,900
Don't you want to know
how I did that?

818
00:47:04,900 --> 00:47:05,800
I'll tell you.

819
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:06,800
They're on a loop.

820
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:08,400
They go around the block.

821
00:47:08,700 --> 00:47:09,300
They come back.

822
00:47:09,500 --> 00:47:10,600
They go around again.

823
00:47:10,800 --> 00:47:12,000
They just go
round and round.

824
00:47:12,200 --> 00:47:12,500
Round and round.

825
00:47:12,700 --> 00:47:15,800
I invited Rita and marlon
for a barbecue on Sunday.

826
00:47:16,700 --> 00:47:17,200
I won't be here
Sunday.

827
00:47:17,400 --> 00:47:20,100
And I need you to remind me
that we need more charcoal.

828
00:47:20,300 --> 00:47:23,300
Are you listening
to a word I'm saying?

829
00:47:23,600 --> 00:47:26,600
You're upset because
you want to go to Fiji.

830
00:47:27,500 --> 00:47:29,600
Is that it?

831
00:47:29,800 --> 00:47:32,100
Ok, ok, go.

832
00:47:35,100 --> 00:47:38,000
I think you should save
for a few months

833
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:40,500
and then go. There.

834
00:47:40,800 --> 00:47:42,500
Are you happy now?

835
00:47:42,700 --> 00:47:45,400
I want to go take a shower.

836
00:47:46,200 --> 00:47:47,300
Let's go now.

837
00:47:47,500 --> 00:47:49,000
I'm ready to go now.
Why wait?

838
00:47:49,200 --> 00:47:50,200
Early bird
gathers no moss.

839
00:47:50,400 --> 00:47:53,300
Rolling stone catches
the worm, right?

840
00:47:53,600 --> 00:47:54,700
[Laughs]

841
00:47:54,900 --> 00:47:57,700
Meryl: Truman,
what are you doing?

842
00:47:58,900 --> 00:48:01,100
Oh!

843
00:48:02,700 --> 00:48:03,700
Truman!

844
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:06,800
Where shall we go?
Where shall we go?

845
00:48:07,700 --> 00:48:09,200
Truman, where
are we going?

846
00:48:09,400 --> 00:48:12,500
I don't really know.
I guess I'm being spontaneous.

847
00:48:13,900 --> 00:48:15,100
Somebody help me!

848
00:48:15,300 --> 00:48:17,300
I'm being spontaneous!

849
00:48:17,500 --> 00:48:18,600
Meryl: Truman.

850
00:48:18,800 --> 00:48:19,300
Forget Fiji.

851
00:48:19,600 --> 00:48:21,800
Can't very well drive
to Fiji, can we?

852
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:24,200
No.

853
00:48:24,700 --> 00:48:27,300
What about
Atlantic city?

854
00:48:27,500 --> 00:48:29,400
Oh, no, you hate
to gamble.

855
00:48:29,600 --> 00:48:30,400
That's right,
I do, don't I?

856
00:48:30,700 --> 00:48:32,300
So why would you want
to go there?

857
00:48:32,500 --> 00:48:33,600
Because I never have.

858
00:48:33,800 --> 00:48:36,700
That's why people
go places, isn't it?

859
00:48:36,900 --> 00:48:39,900
Truman, Truman,
I think I'm gonna throw up.

860
00:48:40,500 --> 00:48:42,700
Me, too.

861
00:48:49,900 --> 00:48:51,700
Blocked at every turn.

862
00:48:51,900 --> 00:48:54,400
Beautifully synchronized,
don't you agree?

863
00:48:54,600 --> 00:48:56,800
You're blaming me
for the traffic?

864
00:48:57,000 --> 00:48:59,300
Should I?

865
00:49:04,900 --> 00:49:07,200
Truman...

866
00:49:07,400 --> 00:49:09,400
Let's go home.

867
00:49:09,600 --> 00:49:10,300
You're right.

868
00:49:10,500 --> 00:49:11,800
We could be stuck
here for hours.

869
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:14,800
It could be like this
all the way to Atlantic city.

870
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:17,000
Let's go back.

871
00:49:17,200 --> 00:49:20,100
I'm sorry. I don't know
what got into me.

872
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:26,700
Meryl: Can you
please slow down?

873
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:29,500
Yes, I can.

874
00:49:30,400 --> 00:49:31,900
Truman! Truman!
That's our turnoff!

875
00:49:32,100 --> 00:49:33,200
I changed my mind again.

876
00:49:33,400 --> 00:49:35,300
What's new Orleans like
this time of year?

877
00:49:35,500 --> 00:49:38,100
Mardi gras! Whoo!
Ha ha ha!

878
00:49:38,800 --> 00:49:40,500
[Honking]

879
00:49:40,700 --> 00:49:43,000
Whoo!

880
00:49:43,100 --> 00:49:46,100
Look, Meryl, same road,
no cars. It's magic.

881
00:49:49,300 --> 00:49:49,900
Ha ha ha!

882
00:49:50,100 --> 00:49:52,300
You let me out. You're
not right in the head.

883
00:49:52,500 --> 00:49:54,700
You want to destroy
yourself, do it on your own.

884
00:49:54,900 --> 00:49:57,700
I think I'd like
a little company.

885
00:50:04,200 --> 00:50:05,700
Oh, Truman...

886
00:50:05,900 --> 00:50:08,500
You knew
this would happen.

887
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:12,000
You know you can't
drive over water.

888
00:50:12,200 --> 00:50:15,000
Let's go home
where you'll feel safe.

889
00:50:17,800 --> 00:50:18,800
Give me your hand.

890
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:20,600
Sweetie--

891
00:50:20,800 --> 00:50:22,600
drive.

892
00:50:22,800 --> 00:50:23,800
Truman!

893
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:27,100
We shouldn't be doing this!
We're breaking the law!

894
00:50:27,300 --> 00:50:28,900
Oh, my!
You can do it!

895
00:50:29,100 --> 00:50:30,500
Please, don't!

896
00:50:30,700 --> 00:50:32,500
You can make it!
Truman!

897
00:50:32,700 --> 00:50:33,800
Aah! Oh, we're over!

898
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,900
We're over the bridge!
We're over the bridge!

899
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:37,300
We're over?

900
00:50:37,500 --> 00:50:39,600
We're over the bridge.
We're over the bridge.

901
00:50:39,800 --> 00:50:40,600
We're over!

902
00:50:40,800 --> 00:50:43,200
Ha ha ha ha!

903
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:47,900
Truman! What
about that sign?

904
00:50:48,100 --> 00:50:50,700
They're exaggerating.
We'll be fine.

905
00:50:50,900 --> 00:50:53,800
Exaggerating?
Do you believe that?

906
00:50:54,700 --> 00:50:57,000
[Yelling]

907
00:50:57,100 --> 00:51:00,000
Oh, my! Oh, my!
Truman, we're on fire!

908
00:51:00,200 --> 00:51:01,200
It's ok.
We're on fire!

909
00:51:01,400 --> 00:51:03,600
It's ok.
It's just smoke.

910
00:51:03,800 --> 00:51:05,100
You ok?
Yes.

911
00:51:05,300 --> 00:51:07,200
Want to do it again?
No!

912
00:51:07,400 --> 00:51:08,300
Ha ha ha ha!

913
00:51:08,500 --> 00:51:11,100
Truman, stop!
Oh, God!

914
00:51:12,200 --> 00:51:12,400
Oh!

915
00:51:12,600 --> 00:51:14,400
So, what are we going
to do for money

916
00:51:14,600 --> 00:51:17,200
when we get
to new Orleans?

917
00:51:17,400 --> 00:51:20,100
I have my seahaven
bank card.

918
00:51:20,600 --> 00:51:23,700
We're just going to eat
into our savings, is that it?

919
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:27,600
I'm going to have to call
your mother when we get there.

920
00:51:27,800 --> 00:51:28,900
She's going
to be worried sick.

921
00:51:29,100 --> 00:51:32,100
I don't know how
she's going to take this.

922
00:51:44,100 --> 00:51:45,500
What now?

923
00:51:45,700 --> 00:51:48,600
Loudspeaker: Red alert!
This is a red alert!

924
00:51:49,100 --> 00:51:50,400
[People yelling]

925
00:51:50,600 --> 00:51:51,600
[Car horns honking]

926
00:51:51,800 --> 00:51:54,400
Truman, it looks like
a leak at the plant.

927
00:51:54,600 --> 00:51:56,500
Back up! Back up!
Leak at the plant.

928
00:51:56,700 --> 00:51:57,900
We had to shut her down.

929
00:51:58,100 --> 00:51:59,400
Is there
any way around?

930
00:51:59,600 --> 00:52:00,400
Whole area's
being evacuated.

931
00:52:00,600 --> 00:52:01,900
Is there
anything I can do?

932
00:52:02,100 --> 00:52:02,600
No, ma'am.

933
00:52:02,800 --> 00:52:03,600
Thank you
for your help.

934
00:52:03,800 --> 00:52:06,400
You're welcome,
Truman.

935
00:52:07,400 --> 00:52:09,700
Truman.

936
00:52:11,500 --> 00:52:13,500
Truman! Truman!

937
00:52:13,700 --> 00:52:15,700
Truman, come back!

938
00:52:15,900 --> 00:52:18,500
Truman! Truman!
Stop him!

939
00:52:19,100 --> 00:52:20,400
Unh!

940
00:52:20,600 --> 00:52:21,300
Truman!

941
00:52:21,500 --> 00:52:23,200
[Whistles blowing]

942
00:52:23,400 --> 00:52:25,800
Head to the left!

943
00:52:31,600 --> 00:52:33,900
Aah! Aah!

944
00:52:40,400 --> 00:52:42,700
Stay away!

945
00:52:46,700 --> 00:52:47,700
Unh! Aah!

946
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:50,200
Unh! No!

947
00:52:50,600 --> 00:52:52,200
No!

948
00:52:52,400 --> 00:52:54,000
Radio:
...Now in custody.

949
00:52:54,200 --> 00:52:56,700
[Truman groaning]

950
00:52:56,800 --> 00:52:59,200
Thank you both so much
for your help.

951
00:52:59,400 --> 00:53:00,800
I really appreciate it.

952
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:02,100
He's lucky to be
alive, ma'am.

953
00:53:02,300 --> 00:53:04,200
Next time, we'll have
to file charges.

954
00:53:04,400 --> 00:53:05,800
I understand.

955
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:07,900
Thanks again.

956
00:53:08,100 --> 00:53:10,500
Good night.

957
00:53:26,700 --> 00:53:29,500
Let me get you
some help, Truman.

958
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:32,500
You're not well.

959
00:53:33,800 --> 00:53:36,700
Why do you want
to have a baby with me?

960
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:39,500
You can't stand me.

961
00:53:39,700 --> 00:53:41,800
That's not true.

962
00:53:42,000 --> 00:53:44,300
[Scoffs]

963
00:53:45,900 --> 00:53:48,600
Why don't you let me fix you
some of this new mococoa drink?

964
00:53:48,800 --> 00:53:51,100
All natural cocoa beans
from the upper slopes

965
00:53:51,300 --> 00:53:53,400
of mount Nicaragua.
No artificial sweeteners.

966
00:53:53,600 --> 00:53:56,400
What the hell
are you talking about?

967
00:53:57,200 --> 00:53:58,100
Who are you talking to?

968
00:53:58,400 --> 00:54:01,400
I've tasted other cocoas.
This is the best.

969
00:54:02,100 --> 00:54:05,200
What the hell does this
have to do with anything?

970
00:54:06,900 --> 00:54:08,300
Tell me what's happening!

971
00:54:08,500 --> 00:54:11,500
You're having a nervous
breakdown, that's what.

972
00:54:11,900 --> 00:54:14,700
You're part of this,
aren't you?

973
00:54:17,500 --> 00:54:19,000
Truman!
Meryl!

974
00:54:19,200 --> 00:54:21,800
You...Are...Scaring me!

975
00:54:22,200 --> 00:54:24,300
No, you're scaring me, Meryl.

976
00:54:24,500 --> 00:54:27,300
What are you going to do?
Dice me?

977
00:54:28,200 --> 00:54:29,400
Slice me
and peel me?

978
00:54:29,600 --> 00:54:31,300
There are
so many choices!

979
00:54:31,500 --> 00:54:33,900
Aah! Do something!

980
00:54:35,800 --> 00:54:37,100
What?

981
00:54:37,400 --> 00:54:39,900
What did you say?
Who are you talking to?

982
00:54:40,100 --> 00:54:42,500
Nothing. I didn't
say anything.

983
00:54:42,700 --> 00:54:44,300
I didn't
say anything.

984
00:54:44,500 --> 00:54:45,700
You said,
"do something."

985
00:54:45,900 --> 00:54:47,700
No, I didn't. I wasn't
talking to anybody.

986
00:54:47,900 --> 00:54:49,000
Talk to me!

987
00:54:49,200 --> 00:54:49,600
[Banging]

988
00:54:49,800 --> 00:54:51,500
I don't know anything!
Please stop!

989
00:54:51,700 --> 00:54:53,800
Stay where
you are!

990
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:56,300
Truman?

991
00:54:57,600 --> 00:54:58,400
Truman?

992
00:54:58,600 --> 00:55:01,300
Oh, thank God!
Oh, thank God!

993
00:55:03,500 --> 00:55:05,300
[Sobbing]

994
00:55:05,500 --> 00:55:07,600
How can anyone
expect me

995
00:55:07,800 --> 00:55:10,600
to carry on under
these conditions?

996
00:55:10,900 --> 00:55:13,100
It's unprofessional!

997
00:55:13,300 --> 00:55:15,700
Shh, it's ok.

998
00:55:17,600 --> 00:55:19,500
Everything's
gonna be ok.

999
00:55:19,700 --> 00:55:20,600
Oh, God!

1000
00:55:20,800 --> 00:55:23,400
It's all
gonna be fine.

1001
00:55:25,300 --> 00:55:28,100
I don't know what
to think, marlon.

1002
00:55:31,600 --> 00:55:34,300
Maybe I'm losing
my mind, but...

1003
00:55:37,800 --> 00:55:41,000
It feels like the whole world
revolves around me somehow.

1004
00:55:43,300 --> 00:55:46,200
That's a lot of world
for one man, Truman.

1005
00:55:48,300 --> 00:55:51,100
Sure that's not
wishful thinking?

1006
00:55:51,200 --> 00:55:52,800
You wishing you'd made

1007
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,000
something more
out of yourself?

1008
00:55:55,200 --> 00:55:57,000
Come on, who hasn't
sat in the John,

1009
00:55:57,200 --> 00:56:00,400
had an imaginary interview
on seahaven tonight?

1010
00:56:00,600 --> 00:56:01,800
Who hasn't wanted
to be somebody?

1011
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:05,000
This is different.
Everybody seems to be in on it.

1012
00:56:09,900 --> 00:56:13,000
I've been your best friend
since we were 7 years old.

1013
00:56:13,600 --> 00:56:15,500
The only way you and I ever
made it through school

1014
00:56:15,700 --> 00:56:18,700
was by cheating off
each other's test papers.

1015
00:56:19,700 --> 00:56:22,300
Jesus, they were identical.

1016
00:56:23,500 --> 00:56:26,300
But I always felt safe
knowing that.

1017
00:56:27,100 --> 00:56:28,800
'Cause whatever
the answer was,

1018
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:32,000
we were right together
and we were wrong together.

1019
00:56:33,600 --> 00:56:36,600
Remember when I stayed up
all night in your tent

1020
00:56:36,800 --> 00:56:39,700
'cause you wanted
to play north pole?

1021
00:56:40,200 --> 00:56:41,500
And I got pneumonia?

1022
00:56:41,700 --> 00:56:43,400
[Laughing]

1023
00:56:43,600 --> 00:56:45,300
You remember that?

1024
00:56:45,500 --> 00:56:48,400
You were out of school
for about a month.

1025
00:56:53,800 --> 00:56:56,900
You're the closest thing
I ever had to a brother.

1026
00:57:03,900 --> 00:57:06,100
I know that things...

1027
00:57:06,300 --> 00:57:08,800
Haven't really worked
out for either of us

1028
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:11,800
like we used to
dream they would.

1029
00:57:11,900 --> 00:57:12,700
I know that feeling,

1030
00:57:12,900 --> 00:57:15,900
when it's like everything's
slipping away...

1031
00:57:16,800 --> 00:57:18,600
You don't want
to believe it,

1032
00:57:18,800 --> 00:57:21,700
so you look for answers
somewhere else, but...

1033
00:57:26,400 --> 00:57:27,100
Well...

1034
00:57:27,400 --> 00:57:30,200
Christof:
But, well, the point is...

1035
00:57:31,300 --> 00:57:34,200
I'd gladly walk in front
of traffic for you.

1036
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:39,500
Marlon: Well...

1037
00:57:39,700 --> 00:57:41,100
The point is,
I would gladly

1038
00:57:41,300 --> 00:57:43,800
step in front of traffic
for you, Truman.

1039
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:47,000
And the last thing
I'd ever do is lie to you.

1040
00:57:49,800 --> 00:57:52,800
And the last thing
that I would ever do...

1041
00:57:55,800 --> 00:57:58,200
Is lie to you.

1042
00:58:00,100 --> 00:58:02,900
I mean, think about it,
Truman.

1043
00:58:02,900 --> 00:58:05,600
If everybody
is in on it...

1044
00:58:06,800 --> 00:58:09,500
I'd have to be
in on it, too.

1045
00:58:18,200 --> 00:58:21,000
I'm not in on it,
Truman, because...

1046
00:58:21,800 --> 00:58:24,200
There is no "it."

1047
00:58:27,100 --> 00:58:30,000
You were right about
one thing, though.

1048
00:58:31,100 --> 00:58:33,000
What's that?

1049
00:58:33,200 --> 00:58:36,000
The thing that
started all this.

1050
00:58:50,800 --> 00:58:53,500
Yep. I found him
for you, Truman.

1051
00:58:54,200 --> 00:58:56,400
That's why
I came by tonight.

1052
00:58:56,600 --> 00:58:59,500
I'm sure he's got
quite a story to tell.

1053
00:59:03,800 --> 00:59:06,200
Go to him.

1054
00:59:11,500 --> 00:59:13,300
Easy on the fog.

1055
00:59:13,500 --> 00:59:14,800
[Keyboard clicking]

1056
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:17,500
Stand by, crane cam.

1057
00:59:18,200 --> 00:59:20,600
Crane cam.

1058
00:59:27,400 --> 00:59:29,900
Button cam 3.

1059
00:59:40,700 --> 00:59:43,300
I never stopped believing.

1060
00:59:46,300 --> 00:59:49,100
Christof:
And wide, curb cam 8.

1061
00:59:50,100 --> 00:59:52,500
My son! Oh!

1062
00:59:52,800 --> 00:59:54,200
Move in
for a closeup?

1063
00:59:54,400 --> 00:59:56,800
No, no, no.

1064
00:59:57,300 --> 01:00:00,000
Move back and...
Fade up music.

1065
01:00:01,100 --> 01:00:03,500
[Music swells]

1066
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:09,000
And now go in close.

1067
01:00:09,200 --> 01:00:11,800
All those
years wasted.

1068
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:14,700
I'll make it up
to you, son.

1069
01:00:15,500 --> 01:00:17,400
I swear.

1070
01:00:17,600 --> 01:00:20,000
[Music swells]

1071
01:00:23,800 --> 01:00:26,100
Dad.

1072
01:00:26,800 --> 01:00:29,000
Yes!

1073
01:00:30,100 --> 01:00:32,500
[Laughing]

1074
01:00:37,300 --> 01:00:38,600
Bravo.

1075
01:00:38,800 --> 01:00:41,600
That was a really great
experience.

1076
01:00:41,800 --> 01:00:42,400
Tech:
Congratulations.

1077
01:00:42,600 --> 01:00:44,600
Ok, quiet down.
Let's concentrate.

1078
01:00:44,800 --> 01:00:47,400
Chloe:
That was good work.

1079
01:00:47,600 --> 01:00:47,700
Whoo!

1080
01:00:47,900 --> 01:00:49,800
Tech: Let's get
some champagne up here.

1081
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:51,500
Congratulations.

1082
01:00:51,700 --> 01:00:53,600
Moses: Brilliant, christof.
Just brilliant.

1083
01:00:53,900 --> 01:00:56,600
Roman:
It just broke my heart.

1084
01:01:00,100 --> 01:01:01,700
Well done, everyone!

1085
01:01:01,900 --> 01:01:04,100
Bravo!

1086
01:01:20,500 --> 01:01:23,500
Announcer: 1.7 billion
were there for his birth.

1087
01:01:27,500 --> 01:01:30,500
220 countries tuned in
for his first step.

1088
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:34,000
The world stood still
for that stolen kiss,

1089
01:01:35,600 --> 01:01:38,200
and as he grew,
so did the technology.

1090
01:01:38,400 --> 01:01:39,100
An entire human life

1091
01:01:39,400 --> 01:01:42,400
recorded on an intricate
network of hidden cameras

1092
01:01:42,700 --> 01:01:45,700
and broadcast live and
unedited 24 hours a day,

1093
01:01:46,600 --> 01:01:49,600
7 days a week to an audience
around the globe.

1094
01:01:50,700 --> 01:01:53,300
Coming to you now
from seahaven island,

1095
01:01:53,500 --> 01:01:56,500
enclosed in the largest
studio ever constructed,

1096
01:01:57,200 --> 01:01:58,800
and along with
the great wall of China,

1097
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:02,200
one of only 2 manmade structures
visible from space,

1098
01:02:03,600 --> 01:02:06,200
now in its 30th great year,

1099
01:02:07,200 --> 01:02:09,500
it's...

1100
01:02:12,800 --> 01:02:15,100
What a week it's been.
I don't know about you--

1101
01:02:15,300 --> 01:02:16,900
I was on pins and needles
the entire time.

1102
01:02:17,100 --> 01:02:20,200
Hello and good evening.
I'm your host Mike michaelson,

1103
01:02:20,600 --> 01:02:21,900
and welcome to tru-talk,

1104
01:02:22,100 --> 01:02:23,800
our forum for issues
growing out of the show.

1105
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:26,900
But tonight,
something very special indeed,

1106
01:02:27,500 --> 01:02:29,200
a rare and
exclusive interview

1107
01:02:29,400 --> 01:02:31,700
with the show's
conceiver and creator.

1108
01:02:31,900 --> 01:02:35,000
So, come with us now as we
go live to the lunar room

1109
01:02:35,300 --> 01:02:38,200
on the 221st floor
of the Omni cam echosphere,

1110
01:02:38,800 --> 01:02:41,900
where we'll find the world's
greatest tele-visionary--

1111
01:02:42,900 --> 01:02:45,300
the designer and architect
of the world within a world

1112
01:02:45,500 --> 01:02:48,300
that is seahaven island--
christof.

1113
01:02:48,400 --> 01:02:51,000
Before we begin,
I'd like to thank you

1114
01:02:51,200 --> 01:02:53,700
on behalf of our audience
for granting this interview.

1115
01:02:53,900 --> 01:02:55,700
We know how demanding
your schedule is,

1116
01:02:55,900 --> 01:02:59,000
and we all know how jealously
you guard your privacy.

1117
01:02:59,900 --> 01:03:02,600
This, sir,
is indeed an honor.

1118
01:03:02,800 --> 01:03:03,300
Don't mention it.

1119
01:03:03,500 --> 01:03:05,700
Well, the catalyst for
the recent dramatic events

1120
01:03:05,900 --> 01:03:08,800
on the show has been
Truman's father, kirk,

1121
01:03:08,800 --> 01:03:10,300
and his attempts
to infiltrate the show.

1122
01:03:10,500 --> 01:03:12,700
But before we get into that,
I think it's worth noting

1123
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:16,100
that this is not the first time
someone from the outside

1124
01:03:16,400 --> 01:03:17,500
has attempted
to reach Truman, is it?

1125
01:03:17,700 --> 01:03:20,100
Christof: We have had
close calls in the past.

1126
01:03:20,300 --> 01:03:23,000
Man: Truman!
It's television!

1127
01:03:23,300 --> 01:03:24,400
Yes!

1128
01:03:24,600 --> 01:03:26,100
Yes! I did it!

1129
01:03:26,300 --> 01:03:27,500
I'm on the Truman show!

1130
01:03:27,800 --> 01:03:30,200
Mike: But there's never
been anything to compare

1131
01:03:30,400 --> 01:03:31,800
with this most recent
breach in security--

1132
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:35,000
the first intruder to be
a former cast member.

1133
01:03:36,200 --> 01:03:37,100
A dead one at that.

1134
01:03:37,300 --> 01:03:40,300
Gotta say, writing kirk
back in--masterstroke.

1135
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:44,100
Since kirk started this
crisis in Truman's life,

1136
01:03:44,100 --> 01:03:47,200
I came to the conclusion
that only he could end it.

1137
01:03:47,400 --> 01:03:49,900
Truman! Truman! No!

1138
01:03:50,200 --> 01:03:51,300
[Construction noises]

1139
01:03:51,500 --> 01:03:52,400
That's off limits!

1140
01:03:52,600 --> 01:03:53,600
Why? What's
over there?

1141
01:03:53,800 --> 01:03:55,700
Nothing. It's dangerous.
That's all.

1142
01:03:55,900 --> 01:03:57,600
You've got to know
your limitations, Truman.

1143
01:03:57,800 --> 01:04:00,200
Mike: But let's remind
viewers exactly why

1144
01:04:00,400 --> 01:04:02,600
dad was written out
in the first place.

1145
01:04:02,800 --> 01:04:04,600
Christof: As Truman grew up,
we were forced

1146
01:04:04,800 --> 01:04:07,800
to manufacture ways
to keep him on the island.

1147
01:04:08,300 --> 01:04:09,900
I'd like to be
an explorer,

1148
01:04:10,100 --> 01:04:11,600
like the great
Magellan.

1149
01:04:11,800 --> 01:04:12,300
You're too late.

1150
01:04:12,500 --> 01:04:15,300
There's really
nothing left to explore.

1151
01:04:15,500 --> 01:04:17,800
[Snarling]

1152
01:04:19,400 --> 01:04:22,500
Christof: Finally, I came up
with kirk's drowning.

1153
01:04:22,500 --> 01:04:23,200
Mike: Most effective.

1154
01:04:23,400 --> 01:04:25,100
Truman's been terrified
of the water ever since.

1155
01:04:25,300 --> 01:04:28,400
Christof: When kirk read
the synopsis of the episode,

1156
01:04:28,400 --> 01:04:31,300
he was disappointed
to say the least.

1157
01:04:31,800 --> 01:04:32,000
Jesus!

1158
01:04:32,200 --> 01:04:35,300
I'm sure that's what caused
him to break onto the set.

1159
01:04:35,600 --> 01:04:38,700
But how do you intend to
explain his 22-year absence?

1160
01:04:41,200 --> 01:04:41,600
Amnesia.

1161
01:04:41,800 --> 01:04:44,800
Brilliant. Let's take
some viewer phone calls.

1162
01:04:45,300 --> 01:04:48,400
Charlotte, north Carolina,
you're on with christof.

1163
01:04:49,000 --> 01:04:51,500
Man: Uh, yeah,
hi, christof.

1164
01:04:51,700 --> 01:04:54,800
I was wondering how many
cameras you got in that town.

1165
01:04:55,300 --> 01:04:57,400
Somewhere in
the vicinity of 5,000.

1166
01:04:57,600 --> 01:05:00,100
Man: That's
a lot of cameras.

1167
01:05:00,300 --> 01:05:03,100
Remember, we started
with just one.

1168
01:05:03,300 --> 01:05:05,900
He was curious
from birth.

1169
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:08,900
Premature by 2 weeks.

1170
01:05:09,100 --> 01:05:10,800
Almost as if he couldn't
wait to get started.

1171
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:14,000
Mike: His eagerness
to leave his mother's womb

1172
01:05:14,400 --> 01:05:15,700
was the very reason
he was the one selected.

1173
01:05:15,900 --> 01:05:18,500
In competition with 5 other
unwanted pregnancies,

1174
01:05:18,700 --> 01:05:21,700
the casting of a show,
determined by an air date,

1175
01:05:21,700 --> 01:05:24,600
Truman was the one
who arrived on cue.

1176
01:05:28,800 --> 01:05:32,000
Mike: Incidentally, I believe
Truman is the first child

1177
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:34,200
to have been legally adopted
by a corporation.

1178
01:05:34,400 --> 01:05:35,400
That's correct.

1179
01:05:35,600 --> 01:05:37,600
The show has generated
enormous revenues now,

1180
01:05:37,800 --> 01:05:41,100
equivalent to the gross national
product of a small country.

1181
01:05:41,600 --> 01:05:43,200
People forget it takes
the population

1182
01:05:43,400 --> 01:05:44,900
of an entire country to
keep the show running.

1183
01:05:45,100 --> 01:05:46,800
Since the show is on
24-hours a day

1184
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:50,300
without commercial interruption,
all those staggering revenues

1185
01:05:50,900 --> 01:05:52,900
are generated
by product placement.

1186
01:05:53,100 --> 01:05:55,400
That's true. Everything
on the show is for sale.

1187
01:05:55,700 --> 01:05:57,000
From the actor's wardrobe,
food products,

1188
01:05:57,200 --> 01:05:58,100
to the very homes
they live in.

1189
01:05:58,300 --> 01:06:01,400
Mike: And all of it available
in the Truman catalog.

1190
01:06:01,500 --> 01:06:02,900
Operators are standing by.

1191
01:06:03,100 --> 01:06:04,700
Christof, let me ask you,

1192
01:06:04,900 --> 01:06:07,900
why do you think Truman
has never come close

1193
01:06:08,300 --> 01:06:11,300
to discovering the true nature
of his world until now?

1194
01:06:11,600 --> 01:06:13,500
We accept the reality
of the world

1195
01:06:13,700 --> 01:06:15,600
with which we are
presented.

1196
01:06:15,800 --> 01:06:17,900
It's as simple as that.

1197
01:06:18,100 --> 01:06:19,800
The hague for christof.

1198
01:06:20,100 --> 01:06:22,500
Hello? The hague?

1199
01:06:23,600 --> 01:06:24,600
All right,
we've lost that call.

1200
01:06:24,900 --> 01:06:26,800
Let's go to Hollywood.
You're on tru-talk.

1201
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:29,600
Hi, christof. I'd just
like to say one thing.

1202
01:06:29,900 --> 01:06:31,100
You're a liar
and a manipulator,

1203
01:06:31,300 --> 01:06:33,200
and what you've done
to Truman is sick!

1204
01:06:33,400 --> 01:06:36,300
Well, we remember
this voice, don't we?

1205
01:06:38,700 --> 01:06:39,700
How could we forget?

1206
01:06:39,900 --> 01:06:41,200
Mike: Let's go
to another call.

1207
01:06:41,400 --> 01:06:44,100
No, no, no.
It's fine, Mike.

1208
01:06:44,600 --> 01:06:47,700
I love to reminisce with
former members of the cast.

1209
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:50,900
Sylvia...

1210
01:06:51,100 --> 01:06:54,200
As you announced so
melodramatically to the world,

1211
01:06:54,500 --> 01:06:57,700
you think because you batted
your eyes at Truman once...

1212
01:07:00,300 --> 01:07:01,900
Flirted with him...

1213
01:07:02,100 --> 01:07:03,400
Stole a few minutes
of air time with him...

1214
01:07:03,600 --> 01:07:06,900
To thrust yourself and your
politics into the limelight...

1215
01:07:07,800 --> 01:07:08,900
That you know him?

1216
01:07:09,100 --> 01:07:10,900
That you know
what's right for him?

1217
01:07:11,100 --> 01:07:14,200
You really think you're
in a position to judge him?

1218
01:07:14,200 --> 01:07:16,300
What right do you have
to take a baby

1219
01:07:16,500 --> 01:07:19,400
and turn his life into
some kind of mockery?

1220
01:07:19,500 --> 01:07:22,200
Don't you ever
feel guilty?

1221
01:07:23,100 --> 01:07:26,100
I have given Truman a chance
to lead a normal life.

1222
01:07:28,900 --> 01:07:30,900
The world...

1223
01:07:31,100 --> 01:07:33,000
The place you live in...

1224
01:07:33,300 --> 01:07:35,700
Is the sick place.

1225
01:07:36,200 --> 01:07:38,300
Seahaven's the way
the world should be.

1226
01:07:38,500 --> 01:07:40,000
He's not a performer.
He's a prisoner.

1227
01:07:40,200 --> 01:07:42,500
Look at him! Look at
what you've done to him!

1228
01:07:42,700 --> 01:07:43,700
He can leave at any time.

1229
01:07:43,900 --> 01:07:46,400
If his was more
than just a vague ambition,

1230
01:07:46,600 --> 01:07:49,700
if he was absolutely determined
to discover the truth,

1231
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:54,000
there's no way
we could prevent him.

1232
01:07:54,200 --> 01:07:57,200
I think what distresses
you really, caller,

1233
01:08:00,400 --> 01:08:02,100
is that ultimately...

1234
01:08:02,300 --> 01:08:05,200
Truman prefers his cell,
as you call it.

1235
01:08:06,100 --> 01:08:07,500
That's where
you're wrong.

1236
01:08:07,700 --> 01:08:10,700
You're so wrong, and
he'll prove you wrong.

1237
01:08:11,100 --> 01:08:13,500
Mike: Well, aside from
the heated comments

1238
01:08:13,700 --> 01:08:15,400
of a very
vocal minority,

1239
01:08:15,600 --> 01:08:18,100
it's been an overwhelmingly
positive experience.

1240
01:08:18,300 --> 01:08:20,600
Yes. For Truman and
for the viewing public.

1241
01:08:20,800 --> 01:08:23,500
Well, christof,
I can't thank you enough

1242
01:08:23,700 --> 01:08:25,300
for giving so generously
of your time tonight.

1243
01:08:25,500 --> 01:08:28,700
I think it's safe to say now
that this crisis is behind us

1244
01:08:28,900 --> 01:08:30,300
and Truman is back
to his old self,

1245
01:08:30,500 --> 01:08:33,000
we can look forward to some
exciting new developments?

1246
01:08:33,200 --> 01:08:34,800
Well, Mike, the big news

1247
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:37,000
is that Meryl
will be leaving Truman

1248
01:08:37,200 --> 01:08:38,700
in an upcoming episode,

1249
01:08:38,900 --> 01:08:41,900
and a new romantic interest
will be introduced.

1250
01:08:41,900 --> 01:08:42,400
Mike: Aha.

1251
01:08:42,700 --> 01:08:45,000
I'm determined television's
first on-air conception

1252
01:08:45,200 --> 01:08:46,400
will still take place.

1253
01:08:46,600 --> 01:08:49,600
Well, another television
milestone straight ahead.

1254
01:08:50,500 --> 01:08:51,500
You heard it here first.

1255
01:08:51,700 --> 01:08:53,900
It has been a singular honor
and pleasure, sir.

1256
01:08:54,100 --> 01:08:55,600
Christof...Thank you.

1257
01:08:55,800 --> 01:08:58,300
Thank you, Mike.

1258
01:09:58,500 --> 01:10:01,000
[Birds chirping]

1259
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:17,500
Hey, simeon.
What?

1260
01:10:21,300 --> 01:10:22,000
Is he looking at us?

1261
01:10:22,300 --> 01:10:25,000
Jesus, do you
think he knows?

1262
01:10:25,400 --> 01:10:27,300
Hello?

1263
01:10:27,600 --> 01:10:29,000
Better call
christof.

1264
01:10:29,200 --> 01:10:31,900
Hello?
Come in, major Burbank.

1265
01:10:32,800 --> 01:10:35,100
[Whistling]

1266
01:10:44,200 --> 01:10:46,600
Ha ha!
[Snorts]

1267
01:10:48,900 --> 01:10:51,000
He's back
to his old self.

1268
01:10:51,200 --> 01:10:53,600
Thank God.

1269
01:10:54,300 --> 01:10:56,600
[Laughing]

1270
01:10:59,800 --> 01:11:02,500
That's an unusual
cat, my man.

1271
01:11:07,100 --> 01:11:08,900
I hereby...

1272
01:11:09,100 --> 01:11:11,700
Proclaim this planet...

1273
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:17,700
Trumania
of the Burbank galaxy.

1274
01:11:20,500 --> 01:11:23,200
Is he going?
Hallway camera.

1275
01:11:24,600 --> 01:11:26,200
That one's for free.

1276
01:11:26,400 --> 01:11:28,700
Keep up with him.
He'll move fast.

1277
01:11:28,900 --> 01:11:31,600
Stand by,
all house cameras.

1278
01:11:31,900 --> 01:11:33,000
Morning!

1279
01:11:33,200 --> 01:11:35,000
All: Morning.

1280
01:11:35,200 --> 01:11:36,500
In case I don't see you...

1281
01:11:36,700 --> 01:11:38,600
All: Good afternoon,
good evening,

1282
01:11:38,800 --> 01:11:41,300
and good night.

1283
01:11:42,300 --> 01:11:43,800
Good afternoon...

1284
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:44,800
Good morning.

1285
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:47,100
...evening,
and good night.

1286
01:11:47,300 --> 01:11:50,000
Morning.
Morning, Spencer.

1287
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:51,000
How's it going?

1288
01:11:51,200 --> 01:11:52,500
Hmm, let me check.

1289
01:11:52,700 --> 01:11:55,300
Vital signs are good.

1290
01:11:55,300 --> 01:11:56,500
[Barking]

1291
01:11:56,700 --> 01:11:58,300
Whoa, pluto! Whoop!

1292
01:11:58,600 --> 01:11:59,600
Both:
Good morning, Truman!

1293
01:11:59,900 --> 01:12:01,900
Oh, look who's here.

1294
01:12:02,100 --> 01:12:03,100
Beautiful day,
isn't it?

1295
01:12:03,300 --> 01:12:04,000
Every single day.

1296
01:12:04,200 --> 01:12:05,800
The policy--
we've thought about it...

1297
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:07,100
Both: And we're
gonna take it.

1298
01:12:07,300 --> 01:12:08,300
You're kidding?
Both: No!

1299
01:12:08,500 --> 01:12:10,100
Great! Why don't we go up
to my office right now,

1300
01:12:10,300 --> 01:12:11,000
and we'll sign the papers?

1301
01:12:11,200 --> 01:12:12,900
Uh, next week
would be much better.

1302
01:12:13,200 --> 01:12:14,200
Next week would be better.

1303
01:12:14,400 --> 01:12:15,500
All right.
See you guys.

1304
01:12:15,700 --> 01:12:17,400
Ok, bye now.
See you next week.

1305
01:12:17,600 --> 01:12:19,400
Give me something
to look forward to.

1306
01:12:19,600 --> 01:12:20,400
You got it.

1307
01:12:20,600 --> 01:12:22,200
See, this isn't
about insurance.

1308
01:12:22,500 --> 01:12:24,800
This is about
the great variable--

1309
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:26,500
when will death occur?

1310
01:12:26,800 --> 01:12:29,500
Could be a week,
a month, a year.

1311
01:12:30,300 --> 01:12:32,800
Could be today.

1312
01:12:33,200 --> 01:12:36,100
Sunbather,
minding his own business,

1313
01:12:36,100 --> 01:12:39,400
stabbed in the heart by the tip
of a runaway beach umbrella.

1314
01:12:39,700 --> 01:12:41,800
No way to guard against
that kind of thing.

1315
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:44,400
[Truman laughs]

1316
01:12:44,700 --> 01:12:45,700
Uh, sorry, excuse me.

1317
01:12:45,900 --> 01:12:48,300
Uh, Truman, this is vivien.
Vivien, this is Truman.

1318
01:12:48,500 --> 01:12:51,400
The two of you
are gonna be neighbors.

1319
01:12:51,600 --> 01:12:53,800
Oh.

1320
01:12:54,400 --> 01:12:55,700
I guess what I'm--

1321
01:12:55,900 --> 01:12:58,900
what I'm saying is that,
uh, life is...Fragile.

1322
01:13:01,900 --> 01:13:03,500
Lawrence:
Vivien, your office.

1323
01:13:03,700 --> 01:13:04,400
Sorry.

1324
01:13:04,600 --> 01:13:05,600
What's that?

1325
01:13:05,800 --> 01:13:08,300
Oh, I'm sorry.
Uh...

1326
01:13:08,800 --> 01:13:09,300
You do?

1327
01:13:09,500 --> 01:13:12,500
Oh, great. Uh, let me
take your information.

1328
01:13:14,800 --> 01:13:17,300
[Lawn mower buzzing]

1329
01:13:29,900 --> 01:13:32,400
Ready 2. Go to 2.

1330
01:13:35,900 --> 01:13:38,400
And back to medium.

1331
01:13:39,100 --> 01:13:41,500
And wide.

1332
01:13:44,700 --> 01:13:47,000
Psst!

1333
01:13:48,700 --> 01:13:51,600
I was just trying
to train the kid to...

1334
01:13:52,800 --> 01:13:55,100
Never mind.

1335
01:13:56,700 --> 01:13:58,600
Christof: What's he doing
in the basement?

1336
01:13:58,800 --> 01:14:01,800
He moved down there after
Meryl packed up and left.

1337
01:14:02,100 --> 01:14:02,500
Why wasn't I told?

1338
01:14:02,700 --> 01:14:05,700
Any unpredictable behavior
has to be reported.

1339
01:14:06,400 --> 01:14:09,300
Uh, he--he's just sleeping,
I thought.

1340
01:14:09,500 --> 01:14:11,400
This the best shot
we've got?

1341
01:14:11,600 --> 01:14:12,200
What's to see?

1342
01:14:12,400 --> 01:14:13,400
What's on the clock cam?

1343
01:14:13,600 --> 01:14:16,100
It's an obstruction--
obstruction.

1344
01:14:16,300 --> 01:14:17,100
What happened down there?

1345
01:14:17,300 --> 01:14:20,100
He was just tidying up
his garbage.

1346
01:14:20,700 --> 01:14:22,500
I was gonna call you,
but halfway through,

1347
01:14:22,700 --> 01:14:24,500
he gave up,
and he fell asleep.

1348
01:14:24,700 --> 01:14:26,600
I wanna check on
the setups for the...

1349
01:14:26,800 --> 01:14:28,300
Both: Insurance
convention tomorrow.

1350
01:14:28,500 --> 01:14:30,900
Yes.
Yeah.

1351
01:14:31,600 --> 01:14:33,100
Nice move.

1352
01:14:33,300 --> 01:14:35,700
[Taps keyboard]

1353
01:14:40,200 --> 01:14:41,500
[Beep]

1354
01:14:41,700 --> 01:14:44,100
There you go.

1355
01:14:53,000 --> 01:14:55,400
Isolate the audio.

1356
01:14:56,000 --> 01:14:58,300
Give me a closeup
on his torso.

1357
01:14:58,500 --> 01:14:59,300
[Beep]

1358
01:14:59,500 --> 01:15:00,200
[Snoring]

1359
01:15:00,400 --> 01:15:02,200
He's still breathing.

1360
01:15:02,400 --> 01:15:04,300
[Sighs]

1361
01:15:04,500 --> 01:15:05,900
Where's Chloe?
Yes, sir.

1362
01:15:06,100 --> 01:15:06,500
Call him.

1363
01:15:06,700 --> 01:15:07,600
What do you
want me to say?

1364
01:15:07,800 --> 01:15:10,200
Tell him
it's a wrong number.

1365
01:15:10,400 --> 01:15:11,300
[Chloe dials phone]

1366
01:15:11,500 --> 01:15:13,500
[Telephone rings]

1367
01:15:13,800 --> 01:15:14,800
What took you so long?

1368
01:15:15,000 --> 01:15:17,800
Just had to wait for it.
They were busy.

1369
01:15:18,300 --> 01:15:19,200
[Ring]

1370
01:15:19,400 --> 01:15:20,100
Here.

1371
01:15:20,300 --> 01:15:21,800
What's going on?

1372
01:15:22,000 --> 01:15:23,400
I don't know. They're...

1373
01:15:23,600 --> 01:15:24,100
[Ring]

1374
01:15:24,300 --> 01:15:25,200
He came down into the room.

1375
01:15:25,400 --> 01:15:26,900
He did nothing
but stand around for a while.

1376
01:15:27,100 --> 01:15:28,700
Christof:
Shut up and watch it!

1377
01:15:28,900 --> 01:15:30,800
Then we went
to nightvision.

1378
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:32,000
[Ring]

1379
01:15:32,200 --> 01:15:33,400
He's asleep.

1380
01:15:33,600 --> 01:15:35,000
[Simeon scoffs]

1381
01:15:35,200 --> 01:15:36,000
Christof: There!

1382
01:15:36,200 --> 01:15:37,200
Stop it!
What?

1383
01:15:37,400 --> 01:15:38,100
Zoom in.

1384
01:15:38,300 --> 01:15:38,900
On which?

1385
01:15:39,100 --> 01:15:40,100
Under the chair there.

1386
01:15:40,300 --> 01:15:42,700
Simeon: Uh-huh.

1387
01:15:43,300 --> 01:15:45,800
Christof: Enhance it.

1388
01:15:46,700 --> 01:15:47,900
Simeon: Is it--oh.

1389
01:15:48,100 --> 01:15:48,500
Chloe: Oh, my God.

1390
01:15:48,700 --> 01:15:51,700
I...If--he couldn't have
gone up the stairs.

1391
01:15:52,400 --> 01:15:54,000
I definitely--he must
still be in the room.

1392
01:15:54,300 --> 01:15:55,300
Get marlon
over there.

1393
01:15:55,500 --> 01:15:56,300
Right away.

1394
01:15:56,500 --> 01:15:58,900
[Tires screech]

1395
01:16:02,600 --> 01:16:05,000
[Tires screech]

1396
01:16:11,900 --> 01:16:13,600
Marlon: Truman!

1397
01:16:13,800 --> 01:16:15,500
Surprise party!

1398
01:16:15,700 --> 01:16:17,100
Oh.

1399
01:16:17,300 --> 01:16:17,900
Come on, buddy.

1400
01:16:18,200 --> 01:16:21,300
I got a 6-pack of cold brewskis
with our name on them.

1401
01:16:21,800 --> 01:16:23,900
Come on, pal.
Come on, buddy.

1402
01:16:24,100 --> 01:16:24,900
[Squeak]

1403
01:16:25,100 --> 01:16:27,400
[Snoring]

1404
01:16:28,700 --> 01:16:31,000
Shit.

1405
01:16:31,900 --> 01:16:34,800
Marlon, find him.
He's still in the room.

1406
01:16:39,100 --> 01:16:41,300
Come out, come out
wherever you are.

1407
01:16:41,500 --> 01:16:43,000
That's good.
Keep it light.

1408
01:16:43,200 --> 01:16:46,100
I know you're in here.
I'm gonna find ya.

1409
01:16:50,100 --> 01:16:52,600
Check under the table.

1410
01:16:53,200 --> 01:16:55,700
The closet, behind you.

1411
01:16:59,200 --> 01:17:01,400
Huh.

1412
01:17:02,200 --> 01:17:03,300
Gee.

1413
01:17:03,500 --> 01:17:06,300
I wonder where he
could possibly be.

1414
01:17:13,700 --> 01:17:16,500
The lawn cam,
get me the lawn cam.

1415
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:25,400
Don't look in the camera.
Say something. Keep it going.

1416
01:17:25,600 --> 01:17:27,400
Keep it going.
He's gone.

1417
01:17:27,600 --> 01:17:29,000
Cut transmission!

1418
01:17:29,200 --> 01:17:30,200
Cut transmission?

1419
01:17:30,400 --> 01:17:32,700
Cut it!

1420
01:17:32,900 --> 01:17:33,600
[Beep]

1421
01:17:33,900 --> 01:17:34,400
[Audience gasps]

1422
01:17:34,600 --> 01:17:35,900
Man: Jesus!
God in heaven!

1423
01:17:36,100 --> 01:17:38,000
Woman:
Everything's black.

1424
01:17:38,200 --> 01:17:39,300
Give me the phone.

1425
01:17:39,500 --> 01:17:42,100
[Classical music playing]

1426
01:17:49,000 --> 01:17:51,700
[Speaking
various languages]

1427
01:17:52,300 --> 01:17:55,200
I don't know where he is,
but he's gone.

1428
01:18:00,300 --> 01:18:00,700
[Clears throat]

1429
01:18:00,900 --> 01:18:03,500
We've got every available
extra looking for him.

1430
01:18:03,800 --> 01:18:05,300
Uh, the principals
are helping out.

1431
01:18:05,600 --> 01:18:07,700
The crew, too,
so every sector's covered.

1432
01:18:07,900 --> 01:18:09,600
What about prop cars?

1433
01:18:09,800 --> 01:18:11,600
Yes, they've been
accounted for.

1434
01:18:11,800 --> 01:18:13,200
He has to be on foot.

1435
01:18:13,400 --> 01:18:15,100
He has the world's
most recognizable face.

1436
01:18:15,300 --> 01:18:17,800
He can't disappear.

1437
01:18:21,300 --> 01:18:23,600
[Siren]

1438
01:18:45,400 --> 01:18:48,100
[Pluto barking, snarling]

1439
01:18:52,400 --> 01:18:53,800
Spencer: Go.

1440
01:18:54,100 --> 01:18:56,100
Hunt him. Hunt him.
Yeah.

1441
01:18:56,400 --> 01:18:57,500
Go find him, pluto.

1442
01:18:57,700 --> 01:18:59,200
Good dog! Good dog!

1443
01:18:59,400 --> 01:19:01,300
All this fuss.

1444
01:19:01,500 --> 01:19:04,200
If he could just
hear my voice.

1445
01:19:04,900 --> 01:19:07,200
Truman!

1446
01:19:07,500 --> 01:19:08,900
Truman!

1447
01:19:09,100 --> 01:19:10,700
Let me try.

1448
01:19:10,900 --> 01:19:12,300
Truman!

1449
01:19:12,500 --> 01:19:15,000
It's me! Dad!

1450
01:19:16,700 --> 01:19:19,100
Let's talk!

1451
01:19:19,900 --> 01:19:22,300
Yeah, I know.

1452
01:19:22,500 --> 01:19:23,700
Just about done
with the square.

1453
01:19:23,900 --> 01:19:26,900
Got to go back to Barrymore,
check the interiors.

1454
01:19:27,100 --> 01:19:28,100
He's got to be in there.

1455
01:19:28,400 --> 01:19:29,600
Simeon:
Barrymore, huh?

1456
01:19:29,800 --> 01:19:30,000
Uh-huh.

1457
01:19:30,200 --> 01:19:32,100
But what about the college?
Who's watching that?

1458
01:19:32,300 --> 01:19:32,700
I don't know.

1459
01:19:32,900 --> 01:19:34,200
Send somebody
over there, ok?

1460
01:19:34,400 --> 01:19:36,800
All right.

1461
01:19:39,900 --> 01:19:41,700
Take another man and get
down there now, all right?

1462
01:19:41,900 --> 01:19:43,800
I don't give a damn. Just
find the son of a bitch.

1463
01:19:44,000 --> 01:19:47,000
Get some batteries. This guy's
not gonna glow in the dark.

1464
01:19:47,200 --> 01:19:47,800
Just get 'em down here.

1465
01:19:48,000 --> 01:19:51,100
I don't know what's going
on. Reroute it back to me.

1466
01:19:51,200 --> 01:19:52,000
We need more light.

1467
01:19:52,200 --> 01:19:54,900
We'll never find him
this way.

1468
01:20:00,000 --> 01:20:01,300
What time is it?

1469
01:20:01,500 --> 01:20:04,200
It's way too early
for that.

1470
01:20:10,700 --> 01:20:13,100
Cue the sun.

1471
01:20:15,400 --> 01:20:17,600
[People gasp]

1472
01:20:17,800 --> 01:20:18,400
Jeez!

1473
01:20:18,600 --> 01:20:20,700
What time is it?

1474
01:20:20,900 --> 01:20:21,700
Christof,
what's going on?

1475
01:20:21,900 --> 01:20:24,300
Did you know that there's
a rumor circulating

1476
01:20:24,500 --> 01:20:26,600
that he's dead?
You hear me?

1477
01:20:26,800 --> 01:20:29,300
The media is having
a feeding frenzy over this.

1478
01:20:29,500 --> 01:20:30,900
All the phone lines
are jammed,

1479
01:20:31,200 --> 01:20:32,900
and every network has
a pirated shot of marlon

1480
01:20:33,200 --> 01:20:34,500
making an ass of himself
in front of the camera.

1481
01:20:34,700 --> 01:20:36,800
The sponsors are threatening
to rip up their contracts.

1482
01:20:37,000 --> 01:20:38,700
Why? We're getting higher
ratings with this graphic

1483
01:20:38,900 --> 01:20:41,700
than we've ever had
on this show.

1484
01:20:45,500 --> 01:20:45,900
No sign of him.

1485
01:20:46,100 --> 01:20:49,000
Why don't you head back
to town and join the others?

1486
01:20:49,200 --> 01:20:52,100
Everyone else is
at first positions, ok?

1487
01:20:52,100 --> 01:20:52,900
Thank you.

1488
01:20:53,100 --> 01:20:56,000
Everyone's at first
positions, right?

1489
01:21:11,600 --> 01:21:12,700
Simeon:
We've got the light.

1490
01:21:12,900 --> 01:21:15,700
So he's got to
be there somewhere.

1491
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:19,200
We're not
watching the sea.

1492
01:21:19,400 --> 01:21:22,500
Simeon: Hang on a minute.
Why would we watch the sea?

1493
01:21:23,100 --> 01:21:24,200
Sweep the harbor.

1494
01:21:24,400 --> 01:21:25,100
Bring up the harbor cameras.

1495
01:21:25,300 --> 01:21:27,900
Shift all harbor cameras
to computer, please.

1496
01:21:28,100 --> 01:21:29,600
Some of those are out,
aren't they?

1497
01:21:29,800 --> 01:21:31,000
Operator: Yeah.
We have 4 of them down,

1498
01:21:31,200 --> 01:21:33,300
but we have
the lighthouse cameras up.

1499
01:21:33,600 --> 01:21:34,800
All buoy cams, please.

1500
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:35,600
Moses:
What's happening?

1501
01:21:35,800 --> 01:21:38,700
Operator: Ok. Long lens,
short base cameras.

1502
01:21:38,800 --> 01:21:41,400
Moses: Why are we
looking at the water?

1503
01:21:41,600 --> 01:21:44,400
Operator: Pan it,
will you, please?

1504
01:21:46,600 --> 01:21:48,900
Truman...

1505
01:21:49,900 --> 01:21:52,400
Where are you going?

1506
01:21:52,600 --> 01:21:54,600
How can he sail?
He's in insurance.

1507
01:21:54,800 --> 01:21:56,200
Operator: Isn't he
terrified of the water?

1508
01:21:56,400 --> 01:21:57,200
Resume transmission.

1509
01:21:57,400 --> 01:21:59,900
Resuming transmission.

1510
01:22:04,700 --> 01:22:05,800
I got 2 to 1
he doesn't make it.

1511
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:07,900
Man: Hey, I want
a piece of that.

1512
01:22:08,100 --> 01:22:09,900
2 to 1
he doesn't make it.

1513
01:22:10,100 --> 01:22:11,500
[Key tapping]

1514
01:22:11,800 --> 01:22:14,000
Just leave 'em
in the car.

1515
01:22:14,200 --> 01:22:16,500
Shh.

1516
01:22:26,500 --> 01:22:27,800
Let's get off
this mast shot.

1517
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:30,400
We can't see his face.
Go to the cabin cam.

1518
01:22:30,600 --> 01:22:32,900
Cabin cam.

1519
01:22:34,300 --> 01:22:36,000
There. Perfect.

1520
01:22:36,200 --> 01:22:38,700
That's our hero shot.

1521
01:23:03,600 --> 01:23:05,400
Let's get another boat
out there.

1522
01:23:05,600 --> 01:23:08,400
Ok. Listen, Gus, I need you to
talk to the guys on the ferry.

1523
01:23:08,600 --> 01:23:11,600
Come on. Get it moving.
Get it out of here.

1524
01:23:11,900 --> 01:23:13,900
[Grinding]

1525
01:23:14,200 --> 01:23:15,100
Gus: Come on.

1526
01:23:15,300 --> 01:23:16,200
I'm just a bus driver.

1527
01:23:16,400 --> 01:23:19,300
Bottom line is,
they can't drive the boat.

1528
01:23:19,500 --> 01:23:21,900
They're actors.

1529
01:23:24,500 --> 01:23:27,000
How do we stop him?

1530
01:23:37,200 --> 01:23:39,500
Ok, uh...

1531
01:23:40,100 --> 01:23:43,200
We're going to be accessing
the weather program now.

1532
01:23:44,500 --> 01:23:46,800
So hold on to your hats.

1533
01:23:47,000 --> 01:23:48,300
You got that?

1534
01:23:48,500 --> 01:23:51,600
No. I think we're gonna
want to localize the storm

1535
01:23:52,500 --> 01:23:54,900
over the boat.

1536
01:23:56,300 --> 01:23:57,900
You can get
the coordinates for that.

1537
01:23:58,200 --> 01:24:00,900
There's no rescue boat.
He won't know what to do.

1538
01:24:01,200 --> 01:24:04,000
He'll turn back.
He'll be too afraid.

1539
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:06,300
[Whispering]

1540
01:24:06,600 --> 01:24:09,000
There she blows.

1541
01:24:19,200 --> 01:24:20,300
[Motor stalling]

1542
01:24:20,600 --> 01:24:22,800
Come on.

1543
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:46,400
Give me some lightning.

1544
01:24:46,600 --> 01:24:47,900
[Thunder]

1545
01:24:48,100 --> 01:24:49,500
Again!

1546
01:24:49,700 --> 01:24:52,100
Hit him again!

1547
01:25:02,100 --> 01:25:04,600
For God's sake, christof,
the whole world is watching.

1548
01:25:04,800 --> 01:25:06,300
We can't let him die
in front of a live audience.

1549
01:25:06,600 --> 01:25:09,400
He was born in front
of a live audience.

1550
01:25:37,800 --> 01:25:38,700
[Cheering]

1551
01:25:38,900 --> 01:25:41,200
Truman!

1552
01:25:43,100 --> 01:25:45,700
You can do it!
Hold on!

1553
01:26:10,300 --> 01:26:13,000
Is that the best
you can do?

1554
01:26:13,900 --> 01:26:16,600
You're gonna have
to kill me!

1555
01:26:17,900 --> 01:26:20,000
What shall we do
with a drunken sailor

1556
01:26:20,200 --> 01:26:20,700
on behalf of the studio,

1557
01:26:20,900 --> 01:26:22,300
I demand that you
cease transmission.

1558
01:26:22,500 --> 01:26:23,000
Keep running.

1559
01:26:23,200 --> 01:26:25,200
What shall we do
with a drunken sailor

1560
01:26:25,400 --> 01:26:27,500
early in the mornin'?

1561
01:26:27,700 --> 01:26:29,500
Increase the wind.

1562
01:26:29,700 --> 01:26:30,300
Increase the wind!

1563
01:26:30,600 --> 01:26:33,200
[Truman
continues singing]

1564
01:26:33,400 --> 01:26:34,700
I'm telling you
for the last time.

1565
01:26:34,900 --> 01:26:35,900
How close is he?
Very.

1566
01:26:36,100 --> 01:26:37,300
Capsize him.
Tip him over.

1567
01:26:37,500 --> 01:26:38,100
Damn you,
christof!

1568
01:26:38,300 --> 01:26:39,900
You can't. He's tied
himself to the boat!

1569
01:26:40,100 --> 01:26:40,300
Shut up!

1570
01:26:40,500 --> 01:26:42,700
He's gonna drown,
and he doesn't even care.

1571
01:26:42,900 --> 01:26:44,400
Do it.
No.

1572
01:26:44,600 --> 01:26:46,800
Do it!

1573
01:27:29,800 --> 01:27:32,100
[Thunder]

1574
01:27:39,300 --> 01:27:41,700
That's enough.

1575
01:28:11,400 --> 01:28:13,700
[Gagging]

1576
01:29:31,200 --> 01:29:33,500
[Crash]

1577
01:30:00,300 --> 01:30:02,500
Oh.

1578
01:30:03,700 --> 01:30:05,900
Oh.

1579
01:31:51,400 --> 01:31:54,200
Christof:
I want to talk to him.

1580
01:32:12,500 --> 01:32:13,300
Truman.

1581
01:32:13,500 --> 01:32:14,300
[Gasps]

1582
01:32:14,500 --> 01:32:16,900
You can speak.

1583
01:32:17,700 --> 01:32:20,400
[Over speaker]
I can hear you.

1584
01:32:24,500 --> 01:32:25,000
Who are you?

1585
01:32:25,200 --> 01:32:27,200
I am the creator
of a television show

1586
01:32:27,500 --> 01:32:30,600
that gives hope and joy
and inspiration to millions.

1587
01:32:36,200 --> 01:32:37,500
Then who am I?

1588
01:32:37,700 --> 01:32:40,100
You're the star.

1589
01:32:45,400 --> 01:32:47,100
Was nothing real?

1590
01:32:47,300 --> 01:32:48,100
You were real.

1591
01:32:48,300 --> 01:32:51,100
That's what made you
so good to watch.

1592
01:32:52,100 --> 01:32:54,200
Listen to me, Truman.

1593
01:32:54,400 --> 01:32:56,800
There's no more truth
out there...

1594
01:32:57,000 --> 01:33:00,000
Than there is in the world
I created for you.

1595
01:33:02,500 --> 01:33:05,000
The same lies.

1596
01:33:05,900 --> 01:33:07,600
The same deceit.

1597
01:33:07,800 --> 01:33:10,300
But in my world...

1598
01:33:11,500 --> 01:33:14,200
You have nothing
to fear.

1599
01:33:16,000 --> 01:33:18,500
I know you better
than you know yourself.

1600
01:33:18,800 --> 01:33:21,600
You never had
a camera in my head.

1601
01:33:23,300 --> 01:33:24,800
You're afraid.

1602
01:33:25,100 --> 01:33:27,700
That's why
